{"title_page": "Bahraich", "text_new": "{{About|the municipality in Uttar Pradesh, India|its namesake district|Bahraich district}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2015}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Bahraich\n| settlement_type                 = City\n| image_skyline                   = Bahraich Clock Tower.jpg\n| image_caption                   = Bahraich Clock Tower\n| pushpin_map                     = India Uttar Pradesh#India#Asia\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Uttar Pradesh, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|27.575|81.594|type:city_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type1               = Country\n| subdivision_type2               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Bahraich district|Bahraich]]\n| governing_body                  = Bahraich Nagar Palika Parishad\n| leader_title                    = \n| leader_name                     = \n| leader_title1                   = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name1                    = Rubeena Rehan Khan\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_total_km2                  = 34\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 126\n| population_total                = 186,223\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"Census2011Gov\"/>\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| demographics_type1              = [[Language]]\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]<ref name=\"langoff\">{{cite web|title=52nd REPORT OF THE COMMISSIONER FOR LINGUISTIC MINORITIES IN INDIA|url=http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|website=nclm.nic.in|publisher=[[Ministry of Minority Affairs]]|accessdate=20 December 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525141614/http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n| demographics1_title2            = Additional&nbsp;official\n| demographics1_info2             = [[Urdu]]<ref name=\"langoff\"/>\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 271801\n| area_code                       = +91 05252\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| registration_plate              = UP-40\n| blank1_name_sec1                = Sex Ratio\n| blank1_info_sec1                = 892 [[male|\u2642]]/[[female|\u2640]]\n| website                         = {{URL|http://bahraichnpp.in}}\n| unemployment_rate               = \n| leader_title2                   = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]]\n| leader_name2                    = [[Anupama Jaiswal]]&nbsp;(BJP)\n| leader_title3                   = [[Member of parliament, Lok Sabha|MP]]\n| leader_name3                    = [[Akshaibar Lal]] (BJP) and [[Brij Bhushan Sharan Singh]] (BJP)\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''puspa''' is a city and a [[municipal board]] in [[Bahraich district]]  in the state of [[Uttar Pradesh]], India. Located on the [[Saryu River]], a tributary of the [[Ghaghara]] river, Bahraich is {{convert|125|km|abbr=off}} north-east of [[Lucknow]], the state  capital. The districts of [[Barabanki district|Barabanki]], [[Gonda district|Gonda]], [[Balrampur district|Balrampur]], [[Lakhimpur Kheri]], [[Shravasti]] and [[Sitapur]] share local boundaries with Bahraich. A factor which makes this town important is the international border shared with [[Nepal]].\n\n==Geography and climate==\nIt has an samriddhi and naina elevation of {{convert|126|m|abbr=off}}. Bahraich has a warm humid subtropical climate with  hot summers from April to July. The rainy season is from July to mid-September when Bahraich gets an average rainfall from the south-west monsoon winds, and occasionally frontal rainfall will occur in January. In winter the maximum temperature is around {{convert|25|\u00b0C}} and the minimum is in the {{convert|-1|to|7|\u00b0C}} range. Fog is quite common from late December to late January. Summers are extremely hot with temperatures rising to the {{convert|40|to|47|\u00b0C}} range, the average highs being in the high of 30s (degree Celsius). Average annual rainfall is {{convert|1900|cm|abbr=off}} (approx).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dcmsme.gov.in/dips/DIP,%20Bahraich.pdf |title=District Industrial Profile of Bahraich district|publisher=MSME-Development Institute -Allahabad, Government of India Ministry of MSME |date= |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAs of [[2011 Indian Census]], Bahraich had a total population of 186,223, of which 97,653 were males and 88,570 were females. Population within the age group of 0 to 6 years was 24,097. The total number of literates in Bahraich was 119,564, which constituted 64.2% of the population with male literacy of 66.5% and female literacy of 61.7%. The effective literacy rate of 7+ population of Bahraich was 73.7%, of which male literacy rate was 76.4% and female literacy rate was 70.8%. The [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes]] population was 9,584 and 170 respectively. Bahraich had 30460 households in 2011.<ref name=\"Census2011Gov\">{{cite web |title=Census of India: Bahraich |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/pca/SearchDetails.aspx?Id=197909 |website=www.censusindia.gov.in |accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nBahraich is divided into two [[Parliament of India|parliamentary]] constituencies, [[Bahraich (Lok Sabha constituency)|Bahraich]] and [[Kaiserganj (Lok Sabha constituency)|Kaiserganj]]. The former is held by [[Akshaibar Lal]] of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) and the latter by [[Brij Bhushan Sharan Singh]], also of the BJP.\n\nThere are seven [[Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh|State Assembly]] constituencies:\n* [[Bahraich (Assembly constituency)|Bahraich]] - [[Anupma Jaiswal]] (BJP)\n* [[Matera (Assembly constituency)|Matera]] - [[Yasar Shah]] ([[Samajwadi Party]])\n* [[Mahasi (Assembly constituency)|Mahasi]] - Sureshwar Singh (BJP)\n* [[Kaiserganj (Assembly constituency)|Kaiserganj]] - Mukut Bihari Verma (BJP)\n* [[Balha (Assembly constituency)|Balha]] - Akhaybar Lal Gaud (BJP)\n* [[Payagpur (Assembly constituency)|Payagpur]] - Subhash Tripathi (BJP)\n* [[Nanpara (Assembly constituency)|Nanpara]] - Madhuri Verma (BJP)\n\n==Education==\nBahraich has many educational institutions, including medical, technical and graduate/postgraduate colleges.\n\n==Medical facilities==\nThe main district hospital at Bahraich includes a 100-bed unit for special care of maternity cases.\n\n==Culture==\nThe city has its own sports stadium called Indira Gandhi Sports Stadium; it hosts many sports tournaments every year. The city also has many sports clubs.\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Roads===\nBahraich is well connected with other districts of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. [[UPSRTC]] and private operators provide road connectivity to [[Lucknow]], [[Kanpur]], [[Allahabad]], [[Varanasi]], [[Bareilly]], [[Haridwar]], [[Delhi]], [[Jaipur]] [[Balrampur]], [[Gonda district|Gonda]], [[Barabanki district|Barabanki]], [[Pratapgarh, Uttar Pradesh|Pratapgarh]], [[Shimla]], [[Mathura]], [[Jhansi]], [[Jaunpur, Uttar Pradesh|Jaunpur]], [[Gorakhpur]], [[Varanasi]], [[Shravasti]] and [[Agra]]. There are buses for Lucknow in every 15 minutes. [[National Highway 927 (India)]] connects the city to [[Barabanki, Uttar Pradesh|Barabanki]] and state capital [[Lucknow]].\n\n===Railways===\n[[File:Bg train.jpg|thumb]]\n[[Bahraich railway station]] is a main railway station in [[Bahraich district]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]. Its code is ''BRK''. It serves Bahraich city. The station consists of 3 platforms, two for broad gauge and one for meter gauge. Bahraich to Jarwal Road is a Broad gauge station 55 kilometers (34 miles) from district headquarters and lies on Delhi\u2013Barauni line.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.jagran.com/uttar-pradesh/bahraich-rail-line-18579562.html |title=\u092c\u0939\u0930\u093e\u0907\u091a \u0938\u0947 \u091c\u0930\u0935\u0932\u0930\u094b\u0921 \u0924\u0915 \u092c\u093f\u091b\u0947 \u0930\u0947\u0932 \u0932\u093e\u0907\u0928 |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=27 October 2018 |lang=Hindi}}</ref> Plans for converting the Bahraich - [[Gonda, Uttar Pradesh|Gonda]] tracks to broad-gauge have been in talks since October 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0928\u0935\u0930\u093e\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092c\u0939\u0930\u093e\u0907\u091a \u0938\u0947 \u0917\u094b\u0902\u0921\u093e \u0915\u0947 \u092c\u0940\u091a \u091a\u0932 \u0938\u0915\u0924\u0940 \u091f\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0928 |url=https://www.amarujala.com/uttar-pradesh/bahraich/71539017461-bahraich-news |website=[[Amar Ujala]] |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=8 October 2018 |lang=Hindi}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Broad gauge rail line from Bahraich to Burhwal {{!}} Allahabad News - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/Broad-gauge-rail-line-from-Bahraich-to-Burhwal/articleshow/4129523.cms |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=14 February 2009|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nBahraich has an [[All India Radio]] Relay station known as Akashvani Bahraich. It broadcasts on FM frequencies @ 100.1&nbsp;.\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Waqar Ahmad Shah]] - former Speaker, UP Assembly. \n*[[Tahir Mahmood]] - former Chairman, National Minorities Commission\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://bahraich.nic.in/history Bahraich District Govt. of Uttar Pradesh, Brief History ]\n*[http://bahraichnpp.in Municipal Board Of Bahraich Website  ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051027181845/http://x5.putfile.com/2/5303525754.jpg Location & Road Map of Bahraich]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050214105618/http://behraich.nic.in/favorite.htm Bahraich - Places of Interest]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101010141215/http://indianmuslims.info/book/export/html/421 Muslims in Bahraich, UP's Most Marginalised District]\n\n\n{{Geographic Location\n| Centre    = Bahraich\n| North     = [[Nanpara]]\n| Northwest = [[Lakhimpur, Uttar Pradesh|Lakhimpur]]\n| Northeast = [[Bhinga]]\n| East      = [[Balrampur]]\n| Southeast = [[Faizabad]]\n| South     = [[Gonda, Uttar Pradesh|Gonda]]\n| Southwest = [[Lucknow]]\n| West      = [[Sitapur]]\n}}\n{{Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Bahraich district}}\n{{Devipatan division topics}}\n\n[[Category:Bahraich]]\n[[Category: Cities and towns in Bahraich district]]\n[[Category: Cities in Uttar Pradesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the municipality in Uttar Pradesh, India|its namesake district|Bahraich district}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2015}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Bahraich\n| settlement_type                 = City\n| image_skyline                   = Bahraich Clock Tower.jpg\n| image_caption                   = Bahraich Clock Tower\n| pushpin_map                     = India Uttar Pradesh#India#Asia\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Uttar Pradesh, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|27.575|81.594|type:city_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type1               = Country\n| subdivision_type2               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Bahraich district|Bahraich]]\n| governing_body                  = Bahraich Nagar Palika Parishad\n| leader_title                    = \n| leader_name                     = \n| leader_title1                   = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name1                    = Rubeena Rehan Khan\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_total_km2                  = 34\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 126\n| population_total                = 186,223\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"Census2011Gov\"/>\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| demographics_type1              = [[Language]]\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]<ref name=\"langoff\">{{cite web|title=52nd REPORT OF THE COMMISSIONER FOR LINGUISTIC MINORITIES IN INDIA|url=http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|website=nclm.nic.in|publisher=[[Ministry of Minority Affairs]]|accessdate=20 December 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525141614/http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n| demographics1_title2            = Additional&nbsp;official\n| demographics1_info2             = [[Urdu]]<ref name=\"langoff\"/>\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 271801\n| area_code                       = +91 05252\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| registration_plate              = UP-40\n| blank1_name_sec1                = Sex Ratio\n| blank1_info_sec1                = 892 [[male|\u2642]]/[[female|\u2640]]\n| website                         = {{URL|http://bahraichnpp.in}}\n| unemployment_rate               = \n| leader_title2                   = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]]\n| leader_name2                    = [[Anupama Jaiswal]]&nbsp;(BJP)\n| leader_title3                   = [[Member of parliament, Lok Sabha|MP]]\n| leader_name3                    = [[Akshaibar Lal]] (BJP) and [[Brij Bhushan Sharan Singh]] (BJP)\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Bahraich''' is a city and a [[municipal board]] in [[Bahraich district]]  in the state of [[Uttar Pradesh]], India. Located on the [[Saryu River]], a tributary of the [[Ghaghara]] river, Bahraich is {{convert|125|km|abbr=off}} north-east of [[Lucknow]], the state  capital. The districts of [[Barabanki district|Barabanki]], [[Gonda district|Gonda]], [[Balrampur district|Balrampur]], [[Lakhimpur Kheri]], [[Shravasti]] and [[Sitapur]] share local boundaries with Bahraich. A factor which makes this town important is the international border shared with [[Nepal]].\n\n==Geography and climate==\nIt has an average elevation of {{convert|126|m|abbr=off}}. Bahraich has a warm humid subtropical climate with  hot summers from April to July. The rainy season is from July to mid-September when Bahraich gets an average rainfall from the south-west monsoon winds, and occasionally frontal rainfall will occur in January. In winter the maximum temperature is around {{convert|25|\u00b0C}} and the minimum is in the {{convert|-1|to|7|\u00b0C}} range. Fog is quite common from late December to late January. Summers are extremely hot with temperatures rising to the {{convert|40|to|47|\u00b0C}} range, the average highs being in the high of 30s (degree Celsius). Average annual rainfall is {{convert|1900|cm|abbr=off}} (approx).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dcmsme.gov.in/dips/DIP,%20Bahraich.pdf |title=District Industrial Profile of Bahraich district|publisher=MSME-Development Institute -Allahabad, Government of India Ministry of MSME |date= |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAs of [[2011 Indian Census]], Bahraich had a total population of 186,223, of which 97,653 were males and 88,570 were females. Population within the age group of 0 to 6 years was 24,097. The total number of literates in Bahraich was 119,564, which constituted 64.2% of the population with male literacy of 66.5% and female literacy of 61.7%. The effective literacy rate of 7+ population of Bahraich was 73.7%, of which male literacy rate was 76.4% and female literacy rate was 70.8%. The [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes]] population was 9,584 and 170 respectively. Bahraich had 30460 households in 2011.<ref name=\"Census2011Gov\">{{cite web |title=Census of India: Bahraich |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/pca/SearchDetails.aspx?Id=197909 |website=www.censusindia.gov.in |accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nBahraich is divided into two [[Parliament of India|parliamentary]] constituencies, [[Bahraich (Lok Sabha constituency)|Bahraich]] and [[Kaiserganj (Lok Sabha constituency)|Kaiserganj]]. The former is held by [[Akshaibar Lal]] of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) and the latter by [[Brij Bhushan Sharan Singh]], also of the BJP.\n\nThere are seven [[Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh|State Assembly]] constituencies:\n* [[Bahraich (Assembly constituency)|Bahraich]] - [[Anupma Jaiswal]] (BJP)\n* [[Matera (Assembly constituency)|Matera]] - [[Yasar Shah]] ([[Samajwadi Party]])\n* [[Mahasi (Assembly constituency)|Mahasi]] - Sureshwar Singh (BJP)\n* [[Kaiserganj (Assembly constituency)|Kaiserganj]] - Mukut Bihari Verma (BJP)\n* [[Balha (Assembly constituency)|Balha]] - Akhaybar Lal Gaud (BJP)\n* [[Payagpur (Assembly constituency)|Payagpur]] - Subhash Tripathi (BJP)\n* [[Nanpara (Assembly constituency)|Nanpara]] - Madhuri Verma (BJP)\n\n==Education==\nBahraich has many educational institutions, including medical, technical and graduate/postgraduate colleges.\n\n==Medical facilities==\nThe main district hospital at Bahraich includes a 100-bed unit for special care of maternity cases.\n\n==Culture==\nThe city has its own sports stadium called Indira Gandhi Sports Stadium; it hosts many sports tournaments every year. The city also has many sports clubs.\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Roads===\nBahraich is well connected with other districts of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. [[UPSRTC]] and private operators provide road connectivity to [[Lucknow]], [[Kanpur]], [[Allahabad]], [[Varanasi]], [[Bareilly]], [[Haridwar]], [[Delhi]], [[Jaipur]] [[Balrampur]], [[Gonda district|Gonda]], [[Barabanki district|Barabanki]], [[Pratapgarh, Uttar Pradesh|Pratapgarh]], [[Shimla]], [[Mathura]], [[Jhansi]], [[Jaunpur, Uttar Pradesh|Jaunpur]], [[Gorakhpur]], [[Varanasi]], [[Shravasti]] and [[Agra]]. There are buses for Lucknow in every 15 minutes. [[National Highway 927 (India)]] connects the city to [[Barabanki, Uttar Pradesh|Barabanki]] and state capital [[Lucknow]].\n\n===Railways===\n[[File:Bg train.jpg|thumb]]\n[[Bahraich railway station]] is a main railway station in [[Bahraich district]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]. Its code is ''BRK''. It serves Bahraich city. The station consists of 3 platforms, two for broad gauge and one for meter gauge. Bahraich to Jarwal Road is a Broad gauge station 55 kilometers (34 miles) from district headquarters and lies on Delhi\u2013Barauni line.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.jagran.com/uttar-pradesh/bahraich-rail-line-18579562.html |title=\u092c\u0939\u0930\u093e\u0907\u091a \u0938\u0947 \u091c\u0930\u0935\u0932\u0930\u094b\u0921 \u0924\u0915 \u092c\u093f\u091b\u0947 \u0930\u0947\u0932 \u0932\u093e\u0907\u0928 |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=27 October 2018 |lang=Hindi}}</ref> Plans for converting the Bahraich - [[Gonda, Uttar Pradesh|Gonda]] tracks to broad-gauge have been in talks since October 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0928\u0935\u0930\u093e\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092c\u0939\u0930\u093e\u0907\u091a \u0938\u0947 \u0917\u094b\u0902\u0921\u093e \u0915\u0947 \u092c\u0940\u091a \u091a\u0932 \u0938\u0915\u0924\u0940 \u091f\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0928 |url=https://www.amarujala.com/uttar-pradesh/bahraich/71539017461-bahraich-news |website=[[Amar Ujala]] |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=8 October 2018 |lang=Hindi}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Broad gauge rail line from Bahraich to Burhwal {{!}} Allahabad News - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/Broad-gauge-rail-line-from-Bahraich-to-Burhwal/articleshow/4129523.cms |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=14 February 2009|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nBahraich has an [[All India Radio]] Relay station known as Akashvani Bahraich. It broadcasts on FM frequencies @ 100.1&nbsp;.\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Waqar Ahmad Shah]] - former Speaker, UP Assembly. \n*[[Tahir Mahmood]] - former Chairman, National Minorities Commission\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://bahraich.nic.in/history Bahraich District Govt. of Uttar Pradesh, Brief History ]\n*[http://bahraichnpp.in Municipal Board Of Bahraich Website  ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051027181845/http://x5.putfile.com/2/5303525754.jpg Location & Road Map of Bahraich]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050214105618/http://behraich.nic.in/favorite.htm Bahraich - Places of Interest]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101010141215/http://indianmuslims.info/book/export/html/421 Muslims in Bahraich, UP's Most Marginalised District]\n\n\n{{Geographic Location\n| Centre    = Bahraich\n| North     = [[Nanpara]]\n| Northwest = [[Lakhimpur, Uttar Pradesh|Lakhimpur]]\n| Northeast = [[Bhinga]]\n| East      = [[Balrampur]]\n| Southeast = [[Faizabad]]\n| South     = [[Gonda, Uttar Pradesh|Gonda]]\n| Southwest = [[Lucknow]]\n| West      = [[Sitapur]]\n}}\n{{Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Bahraich district}}\n{{Devipatan division topics}}\n\n[[Category:Bahraich]]\n[[Category: Cities and towns in Bahraich district]]\n[[Category: Cities in Uttar Pradesh]]\n", "n